\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Motivation of Non-Competes project
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Nicolas Fernandez-Arias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Add tomorrow: handwritten notes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Main idea: hard to control for what causes all of the differences, but we
 can argue with a model that the *causal* effects found in the Michigan
 experiment could result from spillovers.
 The idea is, write a model where there is some force that governs both
 migration decisions of inventors corresponding to those in the Michigan
 experiment, and the other relevant spillovers that I want to account for.
 This force is something like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the private value of getting rid of a non-compete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section*
Big picture:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Project goal: estimate welfare effects of non-compete enforcement, optimal
 enforcement policy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Contribution: an answer to the question above that can exploit use of, in
 a plausible way, the differences in outcomes across enforcement regimes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In order to do this, estimate a model of the effects of non-compete enforcement
 on welfare.
 Need a model for this because we cannot measure welfare directly.
 Call these parameters 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-compete tradeoff parameters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In order to estimate, need to control for the effect of state characteristics
 on data used to estimate non-compete tradeoff parameters.
 Variety of ways to accomplish this.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Migration story important to the extent that we do not fully observe characteris
tics of workforce in each state; helps us to proxy for this (i.e.
 shows us 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there are more smart people in California
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Decomposition allows for consistent estimation of structural parameters
 governing the tradeoffs involved in non-compete enforcement
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Non-enforcing regions exhibiting more business formation in response to
 exogenous increases in supply of VC funding will then be explained by there
 being smarter people / more entrepreneurs in California, rather than non-enforc
ement being better for business dynamism.
 Similary for other measures of business dynamism / worker welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that we still need to solve the problem of identifying the non-compete
 tradeff parameters in a closed economy.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use estimated structural model to analyze optimal policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Future possibilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The above assumes that the outcomes in a state can be thought of as a function
 of state characteristics, which can then be estimated using actual data
 enhanced with migration flow data (and the results of Marx etc.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Outline of Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Some empirical facts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
California has more tech employment, more tech startups, more job mobility,
 more innovation.
 California does not enforce non-competes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Originally, tech employment / startups were concentrated in Massachusetts
 (which does enforce), but over time they moved to California (which does
 not enforce).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Non-enforcing regions exhibit more business formation in response to exogenous
 increases in supply of VC funding (Samila-Sorenson).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
California (and non-enforcing states more generally) pay the same worker-jobs
 higher NPV of wages, and a different time-profile of wages (Balasubramaniam
 et al.
 2017)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
More enforcement, but conditional on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

requiring consideration
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, increases firm training of workers without reducing average wages (Starr
 2017, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Consider this: ...
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Enforcement of non-competes leads to more emigration of knowledge workers
 towards non-enforcing states (Marx).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Enforcement of non-competes leads to less worker mobility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Should I allow non-competes?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do these facts imply that all states should reduce their enforcement of
 non-competes to California's level?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Three questions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Do I believe that the above has really uncovered the causal effect of non-compet
e enforcement (not accounting for spillovers).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
E.g.
 do I believe (3) is truly 
\emph on
because 
\emph default
they are non-enforcing?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Could there be spillovers? 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The original motivation for my project: of course I believe (7) because
 it is identified from an exogenous shift in policy.
 But couldn't it be that this is only because entrepreneurs, inventors,
 and other high-tech workers relocated to non-enforcing regions (e.g.
 California), as documented in (6)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Can also be applied to the other results, e.g.
 could (3) be because non-enforcing regions attract the best talent? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
I want to decompose the causal effect of non-compete enforcement into the
 direct effect on the region and the effect from spillovers.
 How to do this decomposition, given that I only have one data point? 
\series bold
A model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The game is: can I write a reasonable model in which 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The microeconometric results above hold, e.g.
 (3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The effects of spillovers - entrepreneurs, workers, etc.
 moving to non-enforcing regions - are such that (i) does not necessarily
 imply that the non-enforcing state has the better aggregate policy.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For (1) and (2) for example this model would be a model showing the non-enforcin
g region overtaking the enforcing region.
 Adding (6) and (7), we'd need the model to generate some of the differences
 through migration of inventors.
 (5),(6) suggests a model where workers are being tricked into signing non-compe
tes and losing some of their surplus as a result.
 (3) is harder to justify: I need an explanation for why non-enforcing regions
 spawn more businesses / employment when there is randomly more VC funding,
 that either (1) relies on some kind of spillover, or (2) somehow isn't
 a sign that the economy is better.
 Could be a creative destruction story - without enforcement, there is excessive
 creative destruction.
 You'd expect to see more response to VC funding, since it funds startups
 mostly, but this is not necessarily good for welfare (since they're just
 business-stealing).
 Of course this has predictions of its own that could be tested with more
 data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Important note: 
\series default
distinguish between finding effect of migration, and finding effect of migration
 due to non-compete enforcement.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If I resolve all of these problems, what can I conclude about welfare?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Workers' wage profiles probably summarize their welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
But what about firm profits? These are affected by creative destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
And consumer welfare? This is affected by the resulting growth rate, which
 depends on the amount of innovation that occurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If I had results, purged of the contribution from spillovers, about the
 effect of enforcement on the above 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sufficient statistics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for welfare, then we'd be done.
 
\end_layout

