\begin_layout Standard
Let's get into more detail.
 How do I actually convince ourselves of a causal relationship between non-compe
te enforceability and some economic outcome?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose first, to simplify, that state economies were totally isolated island
 economies.
 Then I can ignore (6).
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Reduced form approach I: if I have a bunch of islands with varying degrees
 of enforcement, and I can observe all of the other relevant characteristics,
 then I could run a cross-sectional regression like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{i}=\alpha+\beta\times NC_{i}+\gamma\cdot X_{i}+\varepsilon_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 indexes the island, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the relevant outcome variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $NC_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a variable encoding the strength of non-compete enforcement, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 are island characteristics that affect the outcome, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an error term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
More general forms, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{i}=F(NC_{i},X_{i},\varepsilon_{i};\theta)
\]

\end_inset

 e.g.
 non parametric, can be estimated if I have enough observations (and enough
 variation across the entire range of values for each observation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The problem is: I don't have enough islands, even to do the linear regression!
 At best, I have 50 states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Further problem: I don't observe the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 So I need to use proxies.
 A model could help in constructing proxies, but hard to see how it could
 be identified.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Reduced form approach II: exploit natural experiments.
 I can estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 in the equation, or 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{NC_{i}}$
\end_inset

 in the general formulation, without all the necessary data points if I
 suppose that I observe an exogenous change in 
\begin_inset Formula $NC_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Best example of this approach is the Marx paper on the MARA in Michigan.
 For every one of the hypotheses above, one could in principle check whether
 they hold in the time series in this experiment.
 E.g., one could check (3) 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Now I can add connections between islands
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
I can put this into the previous framework by adding characteristics of
 other islands 
\begin_inset Formula $-i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

