\begin_layout Section*
What kind of model is needed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Model for an ideal dataset / dgp.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose I have a good estimate / model of the effect of characteristics
 of states (population, other resources, regulations, institutions) on outcomes,
 given different levels of non-compete enforcement, and suppose that I can
 observe these differences.
 Suppose also that these differences are all that is relevant for the difference
s in outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strategy is the following.
 Parametrize the model using (1) characteristics of states, (2) non-compete
 enforcment policy.
 Estimate remaining parameters using the infinite data (for example, the
 ideal result of study (3) above).
 The model's estimates will be accurate because we have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

controlled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the effect of these underlying state characteristics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The data does not exist
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately the above situation is impossible.
 First, I can never control entirely for all different characteristics of
 states and how they affect outcomes.
 Second, I cannot be sure I have enough data to estimate a model of the
 effect of non-compete enforcement given characteristics which includes
 all the possible tradeoffs.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It could be the case that 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 How can I solve this problem?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Just do as well as possible, noting the shortcomings: what additional data
 is needed, etc.
 There are always possible other characteristics that are relevant that
 are unobserved – this can't stop you from trying to answer the question
 by controlling for what you can control for.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose we can't fully observe the distribution of talent across states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Model for a real dataset
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Geography
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Distribution of outcomes must be a function of distribution of resources
 (e.g.
 workers) across regions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Model of decision to relocate: I do not observe all relocation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Problem: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
I do not want to ascribe all migration to differential enforcement of non-compet
es.
 But I do want to match the data on total migration flows, so that I can
 use results like (3) to discipline the model.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Treatment of consideration, bounded rationality: if I assume consideration
 (which is the natural assumption), outcomes will only be consistent with
 parameters biased against enforcement of non-competes - to the extent that
 lack of consideration worsens the welfare properties of enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Model of the allocation of non-compete contracts
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If in the model non-compete contracts are allocated less efficiently than
 in the data, parameter estimates will be biased against non-compete enforcement
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Model of the effect of non-compete contracts on observables 
\end_layout

